1
00:00:03,790 --> 00:00:10,456
So welcome. So all week at GDC you've all been, those of you in industry, have been leveling up

2
00:00:10,496 --> 00:00:14,199
your career. But if you're at this session, it might have occurred to you that there's this

3
00:00:14,259 --> 00:00:20,244
whole other career track in academia. Maybe you're wondering if you might want to crossover.

4
00:00:20,912 --> 00:00:26,214
Maybe you're thinking it sounds nice to never have to crunch to meet arbitrary publisher deadlines again.

5
00:00:26,234 --> 00:00:31,375
You get to mentor a bunch of bright, eager young developers who are like younger versions of you.

6
00:00:31,916 --> 00:00:37,017
They all love games and they just want to be in your class and they look up to you like a god

7
00:00:37,097 --> 00:00:40,078
because you've got industry experience and that's where they want to be.

8
00:00:40,859 --> 00:00:44,642
you get summers off, and you get so you can make games,

9
00:00:44,722 --> 00:00:46,503
and not just games for profit motive,

10
00:00:46,623 --> 00:00:49,666
but just wonderful games that come from your heart,

11
00:00:50,206 --> 00:00:51,607
something along those lines maybe.

12
00:00:52,748 --> 00:00:55,370
And if your mental image is something like that,

13
00:00:56,291 --> 00:01:00,895
then you have about as good an idea

14
00:01:00,935 --> 00:01:02,576
of what it's really like in academia

15
00:01:02,636 --> 00:01:06,159
that then grandma's boy has to the actual game industry.

16
00:01:07,785 --> 00:01:09,467
Don't worry though, we've got half an hour here.

17
00:01:09,507 --> 00:01:11,089
So let's cover some reality.

18
00:01:12,651 --> 00:01:14,633
So first and most important thing is that saying

19
00:01:14,673 --> 00:01:17,997
you're a faculty is like saying I'm a game developer.

20
00:01:18,297 --> 00:01:19,839
There are many different kinds

21
00:01:20,160 --> 00:01:21,641
and they all work differently.

22
00:01:23,198 --> 00:01:24,519
First is the adjunct.

23
00:01:25,500 --> 00:01:27,161
Pay is generally low.

24
00:01:27,621 --> 00:01:29,483
It's temporary, not full time.

25
00:01:29,783 --> 00:01:32,025
You have little or no institutional power.

26
00:01:32,525 --> 00:01:33,646
It's a thankless job.

27
00:01:34,066 --> 00:01:36,068
You're treated like you're easily replaceable.

28
00:01:36,308 --> 00:01:38,590
You have no job security past the courses

29
00:01:38,610 --> 00:01:39,411
that you're teaching now.

30
00:01:39,971 --> 00:01:42,173
But a lot of people use it as an entry point,

31
00:01:42,313 --> 00:01:45,576
either to test the waters or gain some teaching experience

32
00:01:45,636 --> 00:01:46,136
and a foothold.

33
00:01:46,957 --> 00:01:50,519
On the bright side, it does tend to require minimal credentials.

34
00:01:50,579 --> 00:01:52,800
If you have industry experience, that's a plus.

35
00:01:53,241 --> 00:01:55,782
You usually don't need to have an advanced degree or anything

36
00:01:55,822 --> 00:01:56,223
like that.

37
00:01:56,943 --> 00:01:59,365
So it's basically the academic equivalent of QA.

38
00:02:02,166 --> 00:02:05,809
Visiting professors are like outside contractors.

39
00:02:05,969 --> 00:02:09,851
It's a full-time gig for a fixed period, usually one year.

40
00:02:11,268 --> 00:02:15,111
one academic year. And like a contractor you have all the responsibility of

41
00:02:15,171 --> 00:02:18,594
getting your work done but none of the institutional authority since you're the

42
00:02:18,674 --> 00:02:19,154
outsider.

43
00:02:20,035 --> 00:02:24,098
There's one important difference between visiting professors and outside

44
00:02:24,158 --> 00:02:25,700
contractors in the game industry though.

45
00:02:26,360 --> 00:02:27,301
In the game industry

46
00:02:28,022 --> 00:02:32,545
outside contractors tend to make more money as base salary because

47
00:02:33,533 --> 00:02:36,356
Yeah, you have to, because they don't get benefits,

48
00:02:36,756 --> 00:02:38,798
because they have these dry spells in between

49
00:02:38,838 --> 00:02:39,959
that they have to cover for,

50
00:02:40,099 --> 00:02:43,322
and so it's understood that you pay a premium on that

51
00:02:44,043 --> 00:02:45,484
to cover their extra costs.

52
00:02:46,825 --> 00:02:48,707
Academics are less nice about this.

53
00:02:48,967 --> 00:02:52,331
So usually it's more like visiting professors

54
00:02:52,431 --> 00:02:54,312
make about half of what a full-time,

55
00:02:55,213 --> 00:02:56,294
a permanent faculty does.

56
00:02:57,615 --> 00:02:58,897
But usually do get benefits.

57
00:02:59,788 --> 00:03:03,115
Sometimes as a visiting professor, you can make the case to renew your contract,

58
00:03:03,175 --> 00:03:08,345
but usually if you like the place, um, that you're at, um,

59
00:03:09,055 --> 00:03:13,478
You'd instead be trying to make the case to convert to permanent faculty from there.

60
00:03:13,918 --> 00:03:18,502
And that's about as easy as being a freelancer and converting to full-time at a company you're

61
00:03:18,522 --> 00:03:18,962
working for.

62
00:03:18,982 --> 00:03:20,223
It usually doesn't happen.

63
00:03:20,603 --> 00:03:22,965
And if it does, it's kind of a trial by fire thing.

64
00:03:24,406 --> 00:03:28,169
Some visiting professors require an advanced degree and they're basically the school's

65
00:03:28,229 --> 00:03:30,070
way of saying, well, we like you.

66
00:03:30,690 --> 00:03:34,353
We'd like to have you teaching here, but not enough to actually pay you what you're worth

67
00:03:34,373 --> 00:03:35,514
or be a permanent employee.

68
00:03:35,774 --> 00:03:37,015
We just want to try before we buy.

69
00:03:38,241 --> 00:03:43,388
Other visiting professors are a way for schools to bring in someone that doesn't have the academic credentials

70
00:03:43,748 --> 00:03:50,257
without getting their kneecaps broken by their accreditation boards because hey, they're they're not permanent. They're they're just here for a limited time

71
00:03:50,518 --> 00:03:51,279
Don't worry about it

72
00:03:51,559 --> 00:03:55,504
And while you're there, they'll try and milk everything they can out of you to help boost their program

73
00:03:58,285 --> 00:04:01,948
Next position goes by two names, professor of practice or

74
00:04:02,048 --> 00:04:04,789
designer or something in residence, like designer in

75
00:04:04,830 --> 00:04:06,811
residence, artist in residence, something like that.

76
00:04:07,571 --> 00:04:10,313
There are some arcane nitpicky differences between professor

77
00:04:10,333 --> 00:04:12,895
of practice and resident, but they mostly work the same way,

78
00:04:12,955 --> 00:04:16,517
which is full time with a split between teaching and

79
00:04:16,657 --> 00:04:19,379
actually making stuff, in our case, making games.

80
00:04:20,239 --> 00:04:22,401
These positions are specifically for people with

81
00:04:22,481 --> 00:04:24,782
field experience, so they typically have lower

82
00:04:24,822 --> 00:04:26,283
requirements for academic credentials.

83
00:04:27,104 --> 00:04:31,787
And there's a focus on actually making games in addition to teaching them.

84
00:04:31,827 --> 00:04:33,848
So it's a lot of a practice what you preach type thing.

85
00:04:34,989 --> 00:04:37,111
Naturally with so many upsides, you might be wondering,

86
00:04:37,311 --> 00:04:38,772
ooh, that sounds awesome.

87
00:04:38,812 --> 00:04:39,412
What's the catch?

88
00:04:39,893 --> 00:04:42,855
The catch is that there's very few of these in existence.

89
00:04:43,075 --> 00:04:45,277
The competition is very fierce, so you're not going to get one.

90
00:04:46,077 --> 00:04:49,279
So this is basically the academic equivalent of entry level game designer

91
00:04:49,359 --> 00:04:51,121
or concept artist or producer.

92
00:04:53,881 --> 00:04:55,004
A few of them do exist.

93
00:04:55,485 --> 00:04:56,126
Not very many.

94
00:04:56,307 --> 00:04:56,868
Don't count on it.

95
00:05:02,782 --> 00:05:04,502
Then there's the lecturer position.

96
00:05:04,542 --> 00:05:07,644
This is a full-time position with an emphasis on teaching,

97
00:05:07,764 --> 00:05:10,665
lots and lots of classes, and almost nothing else.

98
00:05:11,725 --> 00:05:13,446
So this is for people who just want to teach

99
00:05:13,566 --> 00:05:14,587
and then teach some more.

100
00:05:15,447 --> 00:05:17,548
Usually, lecturers are not permanent.

101
00:05:18,288 --> 00:05:20,209
Instead, they're on a fixed-term contract,

102
00:05:20,689 --> 00:05:23,230
sometimes one year, sometimes two or three years,

103
00:05:23,651 --> 00:05:25,671
but you can usually renew indefinitely.

104
00:05:25,751 --> 00:05:26,872
So when your contract is up,

105
00:05:26,932 --> 00:05:29,773
you can try and just keep it going and roll it over.

106
00:05:30,594 --> 00:05:32,716
These vary a bit in terms of course load.

107
00:05:33,176 --> 00:05:35,799
I've talked to some people who teach as few as four courses

108
00:05:35,879 --> 00:05:38,101
per term, others that have taught as much as seven.

109
00:05:39,802 --> 00:05:41,184
And just so you understand the math,

110
00:05:41,264 --> 00:05:43,246
when you're talking number of courses,

111
00:05:43,726 --> 00:05:46,168
a typical course, you're talking about

112
00:05:46,549 --> 00:05:47,750
10 hours of work per week.

113
00:05:49,110 --> 00:05:52,932
That's just to, that includes actually lecturing the course,

114
00:05:52,952 --> 00:05:54,533
you know, or teaching it.

115
00:05:54,873 --> 00:05:57,094
Usually that's just like maybe two or three hours.

116
00:05:57,694 --> 00:06:01,076
But then you have grading, you have office hours,

117
00:06:01,756 --> 00:06:02,636
all these other things.

118
00:06:03,096 --> 00:06:04,857
So it all adds up to about 10 hours a week.

119
00:06:05,758 --> 00:06:07,738
If it's a course you haven't taught before,

120
00:06:08,219 --> 00:06:10,620
add another 10 hours a week of course development.

121
00:06:12,014 --> 00:06:13,995
And I see some of you doing the math in your heads.

122
00:06:14,115 --> 00:06:16,497
And yes, if you start with four classes a semester

123
00:06:16,537 --> 00:06:17,618
and you've never taught before,

124
00:06:18,419 --> 00:06:20,000
that means you're gonna be having flashbacks

125
00:06:20,040 --> 00:06:21,762
to your most recent death march in industry.

126
00:06:23,603 --> 00:06:24,584
So at a lot of schools,

127
00:06:24,644 --> 00:06:27,426
lecturers also have very little institutional power.

128
00:06:27,486 --> 00:06:29,848
So when it comes to things like important meetings

129
00:06:29,949 --> 00:06:32,150
about deciding the strategy for the department,

130
00:06:32,451 --> 00:06:33,471
they tend to be forgotten

131
00:06:33,532 --> 00:06:35,593
and they're mostly invisible to administrators.

132
00:06:35,713 --> 00:06:37,415
So lecturers are kind of like

133
00:06:37,435 --> 00:06:39,056
the academic equivalent of game audio.

134
00:06:42,807 --> 00:06:45,190
That said, like audio, it is still full-time.

135
00:06:45,330 --> 00:06:46,411
You still get benefits.

136
00:06:46,551 --> 00:06:47,853
You still make a living wage.

137
00:06:48,493 --> 00:06:50,375
And in some schools, there is an opportunity

138
00:06:50,435 --> 00:06:53,379
for promotion to senior lecturer and principal lecturer

139
00:06:53,399 --> 00:06:54,059
and things like that.

140
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:55,881
Some schools do that, some don't.

141
00:06:55,941 --> 00:06:56,782
You would have to ask.

142
00:06:57,903 --> 00:07:01,084
And most schools are willing to substitute field experience

143
00:07:01,445 --> 00:07:03,746
and teaching experience for advanced degrees here

144
00:07:03,786 --> 00:07:04,626
for their lecturers.

145
00:07:05,206 --> 00:07:07,847
So you don't usually need a master's or PhD

146
00:07:08,167 --> 00:07:10,008
if all you're doing is teaching and no research.

147
00:07:10,348 --> 00:07:11,749
Though if you have an advanced degree,

148
00:07:11,849 --> 00:07:13,150
it does help if you have one.

149
00:07:14,230 --> 00:07:16,691
The downside is that lecturers are also rare

150
00:07:16,911 --> 00:07:18,512
and they're becoming more and more rare,

151
00:07:18,572 --> 00:07:20,653
they're disappearing because schools have figured out

152
00:07:20,753 --> 00:07:22,193
that if they just wanna bring in someone

153
00:07:22,233 --> 00:07:23,054
to teach their classes,

154
00:07:23,514 --> 00:07:25,275
it's cheaper to get the adjuncts to do it.

155
00:07:28,784 --> 00:07:31,985
At the top of the pyramid, there's this thing called tenure track faculty.

156
00:07:32,085 --> 00:07:35,226
And that's what most people think of when they think of a college professor.

157
00:07:36,227 --> 00:07:41,528
And this varies internationally, but in the US, the way this works is you're

158
00:07:42,069 --> 00:07:44,709
what's called pre-tenure for a period of six years.

159
00:07:45,150 --> 00:07:46,850
And I always thought that was odd.

160
00:07:46,930 --> 00:07:48,711
Like, you know, it's called tenure.

161
00:07:48,771 --> 00:07:52,112
You'd think it would take 10 years, but it really takes six.

162
00:07:53,553 --> 00:07:57,116
And you have one checkpoint halfway through to find out whether you're on track.

163
00:07:57,677 --> 00:08:02,702
Some schools just use that as a way to give you feedback of how you're doing and what

164
00:08:02,722 --> 00:08:03,903
your strong and weak points are.

165
00:08:04,263 --> 00:08:07,747
Others actually use it as a checkpoint where they can just eliminate you if you're not

166
00:08:07,807 --> 00:08:08,488
making the cut at three.

167
00:08:08,508 --> 00:08:08,728
It depends.

168
00:08:08,748 --> 00:08:09,028
So, that's it.

169
00:08:09,048 --> 00:08:09,268
Thank you.

170
00:08:09,288 --> 00:08:09,469
Thank you.

171
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:09,689
Thank you.

172
00:08:09,709 --> 00:08:09,889
Thank you.

173
00:08:09,909 --> 00:08:10,089
Thank you.

174
00:08:10,109 --> 00:08:10,289
Thank you.

175
00:08:10,309 --> 00:08:10,490
Thank you.

176
00:08:10,510 --> 00:08:10,690
Thank you.

177
00:08:10,710 --> 00:08:10,890
Thank you.

178
00:08:10,910 --> 00:08:11,090
Thank you.

179
00:08:11,110 --> 00:08:11,290
Thank you.

180
00:08:12,193 --> 00:08:15,197
And when the clock runs out at the end of six years,

181
00:08:15,578 --> 00:08:17,661
then there's basically this all or nothing.

182
00:08:18,382 --> 00:08:21,006
Thumbs up, you're promoted, you now have tenure,

183
00:08:21,046 --> 00:08:23,189
which means you pretty much have to kill someone

184
00:08:23,249 --> 00:08:24,531
to ever get fired or laid off.

185
00:08:24,671 --> 00:08:25,733
You have a job for life here.

186
00:08:26,574 --> 00:08:28,156
Or you're fired GTFO.

187
00:08:29,651 --> 00:08:32,072
Now this sounds like a lot of pressure, and it is.

188
00:08:32,632 --> 00:08:36,654
If you talk to junior faculty in most fields, they'll act like this is the worst thing ever.

189
00:08:37,654 --> 00:08:41,416
But we come from the game industry, and where can you go in the game industry where you'd

190
00:08:41,456 --> 00:08:43,256
get a guaranteed job for six whole years?

191
00:08:44,957 --> 00:08:46,338
I think that's a pretty sweet deal.

192
00:08:46,898 --> 00:08:50,039
Now that is what I am, so maybe you can see my bias here.

193
00:08:52,625 --> 00:08:53,867
That's kind of where the action is.

194
00:08:54,607 --> 00:08:56,669
Now it's worth mentioning some terminology here

195
00:08:56,689 --> 00:08:58,331
because it's different from the game industry.

196
00:08:58,731 --> 00:09:01,774
In academia, if you're tenure track but not yet tenured,

197
00:09:02,134 --> 00:09:04,377
your job title is assistant professor.

198
00:09:05,358 --> 00:09:07,059
That doesn't mean you're assisting anyone.

199
00:09:07,219 --> 00:09:08,601
I don't know why they call it that,

200
00:09:08,661 --> 00:09:09,702
but that's what they call it.

201
00:09:10,863 --> 00:09:15,487
If you get tenure, then your job title changes to Associate Professor.

202
00:09:16,008 --> 00:09:19,331
Now in the game industry, we use the term associate to mean entry level,

203
00:09:20,172 --> 00:09:24,957
but in academia, it means you're finally one of the people we've actually chosen to associate ourselves with.

204
00:09:25,057 --> 00:09:25,758
So it's a good thing.

205
00:09:26,739 --> 00:09:29,639
And after you reach the associate level, later on, at

206
00:09:29,719 --> 00:09:34,541
some point, you can request a try for a promotion to what's

207
00:09:34,581 --> 00:09:35,641
called a full professor.

208
00:09:35,941 --> 00:09:38,802
And then your job title gets shortened to just professor.

209
00:09:39,682 --> 00:09:42,163
So in the game industry, going from associate game designer

210
00:09:42,203 --> 00:09:45,264
to just game designer is entry to mid-level.

211
00:09:45,584 --> 00:09:48,905
In academia, that's going from mid to senior level.

212
00:09:50,241 --> 00:09:52,823
Now if tenure track sounds sweet, there is a downside.

213
00:09:52,863 --> 00:09:56,165
And that is that this is where you usually require at least a

214
00:09:56,205 --> 00:09:57,946
master's degree just to apply.

215
00:09:58,366 --> 00:10:00,227
Sometimes it's PhD or go home.

216
00:10:00,967 --> 00:10:03,009
And sometimes they ask for what's called a terminal

217
00:10:03,069 --> 00:10:03,389
degree.

218
00:10:03,889 --> 00:10:06,371
Now terminal does not mean it's a malignant degree that

219
00:10:06,391 --> 00:10:08,552
kills you, although it feels like it sometimes when you're

220
00:10:08,572 --> 00:10:09,052
going through it.

221
00:10:09,913 --> 00:10:12,496
It just means the highest degree that's offered in your field.

222
00:10:12,576 --> 00:10:16,380
So that does include PhD, but it can also include things like MFA,

223
00:10:16,500 --> 00:10:20,144
Master of Fine Arts, if you're in the arts, MBA for business,

224
00:10:20,544 --> 00:10:24,769
or professional degrees like an MD for doctors or a JD for lawyers.

225
00:10:24,829 --> 00:10:27,792
There's no higher degree you can get for those things,

226
00:10:27,852 --> 00:10:29,654
so those count as terminal degrees.

227
00:10:31,545 --> 00:10:35,107
There's also another position you might hear about from time to time called postdoc, but

228
00:10:35,187 --> 00:10:38,149
unless you already have a PhD, this is not relevant to you.

229
00:10:38,689 --> 00:10:42,811
Basically in the old days, when you graduated with a PhD in a field, you'd either go work

230
00:10:42,831 --> 00:10:45,113
for a company or you'd get a tenure-track faculty job.

231
00:10:45,453 --> 00:10:48,194
But then schools started pumping out more PhDs they could absorb.

232
00:10:48,675 --> 00:10:52,596
so they had to lengthen the pipeline so now there's this like Ponzi pyramid scheme thing

233
00:10:52,636 --> 00:10:56,878
where you've got this kind of sort of position where we like you as a faculty but we're going

234
00:10:56,898 --> 00:11:01,099
to still treat you like a graduate student and then when you're done with your postdoc

235
00:11:01,159 --> 00:11:04,760
then maybe you can apply for tenure track faculty positions or maybe we'll just ask

236
00:11:04,780 --> 00:11:06,361
you to do another postdoc because we're jerks.

237
00:11:09,602 --> 00:11:12,543
So you don't have to worry about that one but you might hear about it every now and

238
00:11:12,563 --> 00:11:13,323
then that's what it means.

239
00:11:14,957 --> 00:11:18,538
Now, if you ever meet someone who's a tenure track or tenured faculty and you want to really

240
00:11:18,578 --> 00:11:21,598
annoy them, you can start by asking, oh, you're a faculty, what do you teach?

241
00:11:22,659 --> 00:11:26,980
And the reason this is annoying is that teaching is definitely one of the things that faculty

242
00:11:27,020 --> 00:11:31,301
do, but we usually do other things, too, specifically research and service.

243
00:11:31,741 --> 00:11:34,682
And for some reason, academics are obsessed with furniture.

244
00:11:34,862 --> 00:11:35,602
I'm not sure why.

245
00:11:36,202 --> 00:11:38,363
But you hear this called a three-legged stool a lot.

246
00:11:40,059 --> 00:11:43,303
So when we talk about teaching, that's not just running a class.

247
00:11:44,264 --> 00:11:45,406
You do have to run the class.

248
00:11:45,486 --> 00:11:47,648
But there's also other tasks that count as teaching,

249
00:11:47,728 --> 00:11:51,233
like designing or pitching brand new courses for the curriculum, which

