00:11:51,293 --> 00:11:54,757
involves lots and lots of paperwork to describe exactly what you're going to do.

251
00:11:55,658 --> 00:12:00,102
Or taking an existing course and porting it to a new format, like we used to teach this in a classroom,

252
00:12:00,342 --> 00:12:01,524
now we're teaching it online.

253
00:12:02,305 --> 00:12:05,348
Or being on thesis committees for graduate students also counts.

254
00:12:05,948 --> 00:12:11,254
And when you're being evaluated in your job, teaching is mostly judged by student course evals.

255
00:12:11,514 --> 00:12:15,178
Those of you who have been to college remember filling those things out and thinking they're completely useless?

256
00:12:15,678 --> 00:12:16,519
You know, those things.

257
00:12:17,960 --> 00:12:24,385
Downside of teaching evals is we have a ton of research showing that they do not correlate at all with how good of a teacher you are.

258
00:12:25,285 --> 00:12:26,566
But everyone uses them anyway.

259
00:12:26,966 --> 00:12:30,369
And at least there are known ways to game the system, if you want.

260
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:35,452
Like inflating your grades to keep your students happy, or being male because there's a gender bias among students.

261
00:12:36,112 --> 00:12:38,534
I wish I was kidding when I said that, but I'm really not.

262
00:12:39,915 --> 00:12:42,437
And sometimes you also get peer review, if you're really lucky,

263
00:12:42,477 --> 00:12:44,658
where another faculty will sit in on one of your lectures

264
00:12:44,698 --> 00:12:46,660
for a few minutes and then try to extrapolate

265
00:12:46,680 --> 00:12:47,681
to all of your teaching ever.

266
00:12:50,743 --> 00:12:55,066
Now when we say research, this is a very broad topic.

267
00:12:55,166 --> 00:12:57,448
Well, sometimes it's more broad than others depends on the school.

268
00:12:57,788 --> 00:13:01,551
But generally what we mean is being a thought leader in your field.

269
00:13:01,851 --> 00:13:06,235
So kind of like what you would do at a director level at a game studio,

270
00:13:06,335 --> 00:13:09,457
except you're doing it for the entire industry and not just that one company.

271
00:13:09,897 --> 00:13:13,701
It's the academic equivalent of the kinds of people in the industry who keynote at conferences,

272
00:13:14,101 --> 00:13:18,846
give well-attended and high-rated talks at GDC, the kinds of people who have 10,000 followers

273
00:13:18,906 --> 00:13:22,869
on Twitter and who have a dev blog that everyone in the industry follows, that kind of thing.

274
00:13:24,611 --> 00:13:28,815
And research is usually judged by three buzzwords, so it's kind of like a recursive stool.

275
00:13:29,776 --> 00:13:32,598
And the buzzwords are peer review, dissemination, and impact.

276
00:13:33,413 --> 00:13:36,134
Peer review means we don't just take your word for it

277
00:13:36,174 --> 00:13:37,154
that your work is awesome.

278
00:13:37,534 --> 00:13:39,755
Other people in your field agree that your work is awesome

279
00:13:39,775 --> 00:13:40,915
and they're willing to say so.

280
00:13:41,776 --> 00:13:44,697
Dissemination means you don't just do really awesome stuff

281
00:13:44,737 --> 00:13:46,798
but you also get it out there and tell people

282
00:13:46,858 --> 00:13:47,678
so they can see it.

283
00:13:48,398 --> 00:13:50,939
And impact means that you have some kind of measurable

284
00:13:51,179 --> 00:13:52,219
effect on the field.

285
00:13:52,560 --> 00:13:55,141
Like other people are actually referencing your work

286
00:13:55,221 --> 00:13:56,121
and building off of it.

287
00:13:56,841 --> 00:13:58,382
So how many people here are game designers?

288
00:13:59,482 --> 00:14:01,383
Okay, how many of you have read the MDA framework?

289
00:14:02,458 --> 00:14:03,338
Right? Impact.

290
00:14:05,740 --> 00:14:09,323
So schools vary in terms of what counts as research and what doesn't.

291
00:14:09,703 --> 00:14:14,066
The traditional academic form of research is getting published in peer-reviewed academic journals,

292
00:14:14,586 --> 00:14:18,869
and you typically want a high-quality journal that has a high rejection rate, because that's peer review,

293
00:14:19,730 --> 00:14:21,591
wide viewership, because that's dissemination,

294
00:14:22,111 --> 00:14:25,274
and you want your article to be cited a lot by other people, because that's impact.

295
00:14:26,334 --> 00:14:29,357
Usually, you can count speaking at conferences as part of research.

296
00:14:29,958 --> 00:14:33,120
Again, a high reject rate makes it more significant if you're speaking there.

297
00:14:33,581 --> 00:14:37,284
You can also show impact by numbers of people who attended your talk, people who referenced

298
00:14:37,304 --> 00:14:41,967
the talk later in their work, and also things like audience ratings at GDC or best talk

299
00:14:42,028 --> 00:14:43,809
or best paper awards at other conferences.

300
00:14:44,650 --> 00:14:48,153
Some conferences publish their proceedings in a journal, so you kind of get two for one.

301
00:14:48,193 --> 00:14:51,495
You get a publication and a research, or and a conference speaking.

302
00:14:52,336 --> 00:14:56,562
And writing textbooks can count as scholarship, and your success metric there, for once, is

303
00:14:56,662 --> 00:14:58,064
actually the same as your publisher.

304
00:14:58,225 --> 00:15:02,050
You want the book widely adopted in classes and industry with really high sales numbers.

305
00:15:05,331 --> 00:15:07,533
Bringing in grants is something you might be judged on.

306
00:15:07,873 --> 00:15:09,614
A grant means you're basically saying,

307
00:15:09,834 --> 00:15:12,756
hey, I convinced other people to give me lots of money

308
00:15:13,077 --> 00:15:15,098
to do my work, therefore I have value.

309
00:15:16,239 --> 00:15:18,520
Realistically, if you're consistently bringing in

310
00:15:18,580 --> 00:15:20,802
more money than your salary from the school,

311
00:15:21,322 --> 00:15:23,584
then they're never going to fire you no matter what

312
00:15:23,644 --> 00:15:25,605
because you're a net positive on their cash flow.

313
00:15:26,586 --> 00:15:28,327
Also realistically, most of us who come from

314
00:15:28,367 --> 00:15:29,548
the game industry are gonna have

315
00:15:29,568 --> 00:15:31,109
a really hard time doing that.

316
00:15:33,465 --> 00:15:36,927
Another way to disseminate your work is during exhibitions and festivals.

317
00:15:37,267 --> 00:15:41,449
Having your game nominated for an award at IGF. Having your game accepted to a

318
00:15:41,509 --> 00:15:45,451
festival like Indiecade or Boston Fig or different games or other game festivals.

319
00:15:46,152 --> 00:15:49,493
This is particularly important for those of us who make games and that that is

320
00:15:49,573 --> 00:15:52,175
our primary form of research or scholarship.

321
00:15:52,615 --> 00:15:55,356
And those of you who would like to do research in the form of making games

322
00:15:55,396 --> 00:15:58,758
should now be sufficiently terrified at how competitive these festivals are.

323
00:16:01,508 --> 00:16:05,993
The last leg of our three-legged stool is service. And we use the word service in the same

324
00:16:06,133 --> 00:16:11,900
meaning as community service or public service. This is the easy part. You can serve on

325
00:16:11,940 --> 00:16:16,065
committees at your school, be a reviewer who green lights talks or papers for journals or

326
00:16:16,085 --> 00:16:20,310
conferences, judging games for IGF or Indicade or other competitions.

327
00:16:20,871 --> 00:16:22,692
doing academic advising for students,

328
00:16:23,192 --> 00:16:25,073
being a faculty advisor for student clubs

329
00:16:25,113 --> 00:16:26,974
or organizations like a game dev club,

330
00:16:27,434 --> 00:16:30,076
organizing on-campus events like Global Game Jam

331
00:16:30,116 --> 00:16:31,016
or other game jams,

332
00:16:31,597 --> 00:16:34,178
doing, you can also do service outside of campus

333
00:16:34,198 --> 00:16:36,119
but in the local community, that also counts.

334
00:16:36,719 --> 00:16:39,341
So giving workshops in game design at local high schools

335
00:16:39,421 --> 00:16:41,402
or a local scouts troop, something like that.

336
00:16:42,443 --> 00:16:44,024
You can also do service

337
00:16:44,144 --> 00:16:46,285
in the game development community itself,

338
00:16:47,065 --> 00:16:49,166
doing volunteer work for IGDA, for example.

339
00:16:50,337 --> 00:16:52,298
Surface is easy, and it's a lot of fun.

340
00:16:52,358 --> 00:16:53,939
It's also usually weighted much less

341
00:16:53,999 --> 00:16:56,240
than in your job evaluation than teaching and research.

342
00:16:56,520 --> 00:16:57,881
We usually call it a checkbox.

343
00:16:58,101 --> 00:17:00,562
And there's not actually a physical checkbox

344
00:17:00,742 --> 00:17:03,483
on the tenure form, but it's one of those things

345
00:17:03,544 --> 00:17:05,885
where you just have to put in a few bullet points

346
00:17:05,925 --> 00:17:09,146
that say, yes, I did the minimum amount of service.

