484
00:23:48,810 --> 00:23:51,292
Like, how many of you in industry have spoken before

485
00:23:51,392 --> 00:23:53,693
at some conference or other at some point in your life?

486
00:23:54,033 --> 00:23:55,294
Quite a few of you, right?

487
00:23:55,954 --> 00:23:57,215
So you're not as much of a noob

488
00:23:57,275 --> 00:23:58,936
as you think you are to academia.

489
00:23:59,396 --> 00:24:00,237
You can also write a book.

490
00:24:00,437 --> 00:24:02,418
Anyone here read Raph Koster's Theory of Fun?

491
00:24:03,058 --> 00:24:03,218
Right?

492
00:24:03,558 --> 00:24:05,640
That's, see, impact again, right?

493
00:24:06,140 --> 00:24:08,181
And you don't need to be an academic to write books.

494
00:24:08,281 --> 00:24:09,922
He doesn't have any academic qualifications.

495
00:24:09,962 --> 00:24:11,743
He just wrote a book and now everyone's reading it.

496
00:24:11,823 --> 00:24:14,404
And it gives you academic street cred if you do that.

497
00:24:15,412 --> 00:24:17,613
Another thing you can do is reach out to academics.

498
00:24:17,693 --> 00:24:19,514
We are all over the place at GDC.

499
00:24:19,574 --> 00:24:22,016
We even have our own summit that took place a few days ago.

500
00:24:22,536 --> 00:24:24,217
And just ask about collaborations.

501
00:24:24,698 --> 00:24:26,099
Now you might be thinking about this,

502
00:24:26,179 --> 00:24:28,000
having this image in your mind

503
00:24:28,040 --> 00:24:29,541
of the ivory tower academic,

504
00:24:29,621 --> 00:24:31,422
the person who just lives in their own bubble

505
00:24:31,462 --> 00:24:33,784
doing meaningless research with no practical application

506
00:24:33,804 --> 00:24:35,345
who just doesn't care, right?

507
00:24:35,585 --> 00:24:36,966
Believe me, that is a myth.

508
00:24:37,226 --> 00:24:40,268
That is an unfair stereotype, especially in games.

509
00:24:40,488 --> 00:24:44,789
virtually all of the academics I know, they want their work to be used in the field.

510
00:24:44,949 --> 00:24:46,810
That's why they became researchers.

511
00:24:47,510 --> 00:24:50,871
It's just that some of them don't know how and would desperately like to consult with

512
00:24:50,991 --> 00:24:53,372
actual game devs so they don't get in over their heads.

513
00:24:53,952 --> 00:24:57,173
Or sometimes you'll find a researcher who does know what they're doing and they'd like

514
00:24:57,213 --> 00:25:00,634
to collaborate with industry because it's tactically useful to have industry partners

515
00:25:00,674 --> 00:25:01,594
on certain types of grants.

516
00:25:02,034 --> 00:25:05,075
Or just because they'd like to work with proper developers again and not just students.

517
00:25:06,501 --> 00:25:11,732
If you can bring extra work to your game dev studio that you're working for now from an academic grant,

518
00:25:12,053 --> 00:25:15,160
that helps your game development career and gets you research experience.

519
00:25:16,982 --> 00:25:18,984
And now earlier I talked about degree requirements.

520
00:25:19,164 --> 00:25:21,225
So for those of you who don't have a graduate degree,

521
00:25:21,706 --> 00:25:22,947
you have options.

522
00:25:23,447 --> 00:25:25,288
You can do the job search anyway,

523
00:25:25,528 --> 00:25:27,210
just with a more limited pool of jobs

524
00:25:27,270 --> 00:25:29,291
that are willing to take your industry XP

525
00:25:30,092 --> 00:25:31,993
and substitute it for academic credentials.

526
00:25:32,634 --> 00:25:34,155
Keep in mind, there are fewer of those

527
00:25:34,395 --> 00:25:36,416
and you're competing with everyone else in the room here,

528
00:25:37,837 --> 00:25:39,098
but that is a possibility.

529
00:25:40,185 --> 00:25:42,866
The other thing you can do is you can go back to school and earn your degree.

530
00:25:43,026 --> 00:25:47,668
Many schools have part-time options where you can take one or two classes per term while

531
00:25:47,688 --> 00:25:48,728
still keeping your day job.

532
00:25:49,329 --> 00:25:53,330
Most of you with industry experience are going to kick the ass of most other applicants to

533
00:25:53,350 --> 00:25:56,952
those programs who are coming fresh off a bachelor's degree with no real world experience,

534
00:25:57,352 --> 00:26:00,814
which means you've got a decent shot at scoring a sweet scholarship to reduce or eliminate

535
00:26:00,834 --> 00:26:01,394
your costs.

536
00:26:02,557 --> 00:26:05,299
Or if you have the means, you can go back to school full time.

537
00:26:05,479 --> 00:26:06,919
That's kind of the all-in option.

538
00:26:07,319 --> 00:26:08,820
But that is what I did.

539
00:26:08,880 --> 00:26:10,841
I saved up over really aggressively

540
00:26:10,881 --> 00:26:12,482
when I had a full-time job in industry

541
00:26:12,802 --> 00:26:14,783
until I had a couple years worth of financial cushion

542
00:26:15,123 --> 00:26:16,524
and was able to just stretch that out

543
00:26:16,564 --> 00:26:18,084
by doing freelance work on the side

544
00:26:18,124 --> 00:26:19,405
while I was doing full-time school.

545
00:26:20,305 --> 00:26:24,428
Generally, the higher degree you have, the more doors in academia will open for you,

546
00:26:24,648 --> 00:26:28,570
but also the longer it takes you to earn the degree in the first place, and the riskier

547
00:26:28,590 --> 00:26:32,772
a proposition it is if something goes horribly off the rails in your academic career along

548
00:26:32,792 --> 00:26:33,032
the way.

549
00:26:33,793 --> 00:26:35,314
At any rate, so it's all trade-offs.

550
00:26:36,074 --> 00:26:38,016
At any rate, if you know that you want to be a faculty,

551
00:26:38,396 --> 00:26:40,458
then the rule is get the highest degree you can,

552
00:26:41,038 --> 00:26:43,160
but know that there are occasionally job postings

553
00:26:43,200 --> 00:26:45,262
with lower requirements, and you should keep an eye out

554
00:26:45,302 --> 00:26:47,704
for those and be ready to pounce on an opportunity.

555
00:26:48,184 --> 00:26:50,146
So it's basically just like when all of you

556
00:26:50,166 --> 00:26:51,607
started out in the game industry,

557
00:26:52,307 --> 00:26:54,389
and it seemed like the only job postings

558
00:26:54,429 --> 00:26:56,411
required three plus years industry XP

559
00:26:56,491 --> 00:26:59,013
and minimum one ship title, and you didn't have any,

560
00:26:59,073 --> 00:27:01,875
and it felt impossible, but obviously it wasn't impossible

561
00:27:01,955 --> 00:27:02,976
because you're here.

562
00:27:03,676 --> 00:27:05,138
So academia is like that too.

